-- Stocks in South Africa Fall: Anglo, Billiton, Harmony, Impala, Kairos Move
-- B y   N i c k y   S m i t h   a n d   R o n   D e r b y
-- 2010-10-19T15:41:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-19/south-african-stocks-advance-for-a-second-day-led-up-by-northam-vodacom.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  fell 173.97, or 0.6 percent, to 30,003.08 at the 5
p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up almost 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark
stock index, lost 3.50 rand, or 1.1 percent, to 307 rand. Copper
slumped 2 percent to $8,274.50 a metric ton on the London Metal
Exchange. Shares in larger rival  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ)
dropped 3.65 rand, or 1.5 percent, to 234.35 rand.  Harmony Gold Mining Ltd.  (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-largest
producer of the metal, slid 1.32 rand, or 1.7 percent, to 76.18
rand. Gold decreased as much as 2.9 percent to $1,332.18 an
ounce.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd.  (IMP SJ), the second-largest
producer of the metal, sank 2 rand, or 1 percent, to 193 rand.
Platinum retreated as much as 1.9 percent.       Kairos Industrial Holdings Ltd.  (KIR SJ) declined 4 cents,
or 44 percent, to 5 cents, its biggest intraday slump since
Sept. 7. The mining-gear maker said it expects its first-half
loss per share excluding one-time items to increase fivefold
from a year earlier.  To contact the reporters on this story:
